h3. Problem Description:

http(s)://<JIRA_BASE_URL>/status returns RUNNING as status when the underlying database stops or does not responds.

The status used for monitoring health of the application is not correct.


h3. Steps to Reproduce:
 # Start Jira server with a running PostgreSQL database
 # Login to the application 
 # Check the status using _*http(s)://<JIRA_BASE_URL>/status*_
 ** It will show running status
 # Stop the database configured with the Jira server:
 # Check again the status using with _*http(s)://<JIRA_BASE_URL>/status*_

h3. Expected Result:
 * When hitting _*http(s)://<JIRA_BASE_URL>/status*_, the following status is returned:
{code:java}
{"state":"ERROR"}
{code}

h3. Actual Result:
 * When hitting _*http(s)://<JIRA_BASE_URL>/status*_, the following status is returned:
{code:java}
{"state":"RUNNING"}
{code}

 * The error in the log says :
{code:java}
Caused by: org.postgresql.util.PSQLException: Connection to localhost:5432 refused.
{code}

As per customer description: 

{quote}
We have some mailboxes that users would like to use for incoming Jira issues. However the accounts have no password and are access via delegation in Exchange. Microsoft IMAP provides a way to specify this in the username string, eg. mainacct@acme.com\delegatedacct.
{quote}

And this is not something currently doable on JIRA, as it requires a password to work successfully.

h3. Problem Definition
In a lot of cases, Jira’s Java API returns the object as a mutable object. Sometimes API returns it as immutable interface implementation, but due to dynamic-typing transformation in Groovy code, it can just bypass the interface. 

This could lead to problems with data consistency when executing the Groovy code, for example: assigning a value to the _Issue Status_ (operator ‘=') rather than the equivalence operator (’=='). 
In other words, the end-user _can modify arbitrary Java memory object in the heap through Groovy code_.

h3. Suggested Solution
Modify Jira API for critical actions and return immutable objects to protect the application state. 

h3. Some examples to illustrate the problem
An example of how Groovy can violate the API contract 
* Given these two files:
{code:Java|borderStyle=solid}
interface ImmutableCachedObject {
}

class CachedObject implements ImmutableCachedObject {
    void changeObm() {
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException();
    }

    static ImmutableCachedObject getObject() {
        return new CachedObject();
    }
}
{code}
* from Java API perspective, the object is immutable. What Groovy code does is:
{code:Java|borderStyle=solid}
import groovy.transform.TypeChecked
import CachedObject

void test() {
    CachedObject.getObject().breakJira()
}

test()
{code}
** When you run it, you get:
{code:Java|borderStyle=solid}
Caught: java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException: You broke Jira.
java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException: You broke Jira.
	at CachedObject.breakJira(CachedObjectImpl.java:3)
	at test.test(test.groovy:6)
	at test.run(test.groovy:9)
{code}
** (!) it bypasses the static type guarantees that Jira API offers 
*  if this code did static type checking (note the annotation):
{code:Java|borderStyle=solid}
import groovy.transform.TypeChecked
import CachedObject

@TypeChecked
void test() {
    CachedObject.getObject().breakJira()
}

test()
{code}
** you get:
{code:Java|borderStyle=solid}
org.codehaus.groovy.control.MultipleCompilationErrorsException: startup failed:
/private/tmp/aaa/test.groovy: 6: [Static type checking] - Cannot find matching method ImmutableCachedObject#breakJira(). Please check if the declared type is correct and if the method exists.
 @ line 6, column 5.
       CachedObject.getObject().breakJira()
       ^

1 error
{code}
 ** (/) The code wouldn’t run, because Groovy was intructed to respect API boundaries.


In case of Jira [IssueConstants|https://docs.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/api/8.5.1/com/atlassian/jira/issue/IssueConstants.html] API doesn't have a setters. 

h3. Workaround 
None

# OH SEONG KOOI*_+{color:#403294}{color:#0747A6}~[mailto:(/)
{noformat}
*no* further _formatting_ is done here
{noformat}
]~{color}{color}+_*

h3. Issue Summary
When creating a project version, The Java API method [VersionManager.createVersion|https://docs.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/api/latest/com/atlassian/jira/project/version/VersionManager.html#createVersion-java.lang.String-java.util.Date-java.util.Date-java.lang.String-java.lang.Long-java.lang.Long-boolean-] does not check if there are versions with the same name in the project. This may result in duplicate version names and can cause bigger issues. 

The method should now allow the creation of duplicate versions, especially that the JIRA REST API enforces uniqueness on versions names per project. 

Since this seems to be an omission, it's logged as a bug. 

h3. Steps to Reproduce
* Use the method in a Groovy script to create a project version with the same name as an existing one. 
* Groovy scripts can be executed in Jira via the ScirptRunner app. 
* Here's a Groovy script to duplicate all versions: 
{code:java|title=duplicate_versions.groovy|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#6a8eb3|titleBGColor=#f8f8f8|bgColor=#f8f8f8}
import com.atlassian.jira.component.ComponentAccessor
import com.atlassian.jira.project.Project
import com.atlassian.jira.project.version.Version

log.warn("starting")
def projectManager = ComponentAccessor.getProjectManager()
def versionManager = ComponentAccessor.getVersionManager()
def user = ComponentAccessor.getJiraAuthenticationContext().getLoggedInUser()
def projects = projectManager.getProjects()

def versions = versionManager.getAllVersionsForProjects(projects, true)
for (version in versions) {
    log.warn(version.getName() + ", " + version.getId() + "), " + version.getProject().getName() + " (" + version.getProject().getId() + ")")
    versionManager.createVersion(version.getName(),version.getStartDate(), version.getReleaseDate(), version.getDescription(), version.getProject().getId(), version.getId(), version.isReleased())
    log.warn(version.getName() + ", " + version.getId() + "), " + version.getProject().getName() + " (" + version.getProject().getId() + ")")
    
}
{code}

h3. Expected Results
Jira shouldn't allow duplicate project versions to created and the script should exit with an exception. 

h3. Actual Results
Duplicate project versions are created. 

h3. Workaround
Third-party app developers should program defensively and check for the existence of versions with the same name before creating new ones.

h3. Problem Definition

Putting some functions defined in [Advanced searching \- functions reference|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jiracoreserver/advanced-searching-functions-reference-939937722.html] and field value in same IN () parenthesis doesn't return both result as it doesn't query with OR condition. 
  
For example, the following JQL will return all projects' tickets that is lead by the searcher.  
{code:sql}
project in projectsLeadByUser() 
{code}

Meanwhile putting TEST project in the IN() parenthesis is expected to return all projects' tickets that searcher leads + TEST project.  
But it actually returns only the tickets in TEST project.
{code:sql}
project in (projectsLeadByUser(), TEST) 
{code}

You have to tweak the JQL as below to return the expected ones.
{code:sql}
(project in projectsLeadByUser() OR project in (TEST))
{code}

This isn't intuitive as IN() operator is usually expected to search with OR condition. 


I've observed this behavior at least on 
* {{projectsLeadByUser()}} 
* {{projectsWhereUserHasPermission()}} 
* {{projectsWhereUserHasRole()}}



h3. Suggested Solution

Allow IN operator to handle functions and field value in same parenthesis to search with OR condition.

h3. Problem Definition
The field *issueLinkType* does not support the operator *IS*, which makes it impossible to write a JQL query to exclude a specific issue link type from its results. That occurs because issues without links will also be matched, and there's no way to specify a null value for *issueLinkType*.

For example, when running the JQL query below:
{code}
project in (SCRUM) AND issuetype = story AND issueLinkType != blocks AND status not in (Done)
{code}

All issues having an *issueLinkType* different than *blocks* will be returned, *including issues without any links.*

h3. Suggested Solution
Implement support for the operator *IS* on the field *issueLinkType*. That would allow the JQL query above to be rewritten as:
{code}
project in (SCRUM) AND issuetype = story AND issueLinkType != blocks AND issueLinkType IS NOT EMPTY AND status not in (Done)
{code}

Which would return all issues in project SCRUM, having issuetype *Story*, having at least one issue link type different than *blocks*, and having a *status* different than *Done*.

h3. Workaround 
One can create a special saved filter containing all currently available issue link types and use nested filters.

The downside is that any modifications to issue link types, such as adding a new one, or renaming/deleting existing ones, would break this functionality until the filter is updated.

{code:title=Filter named "All issue link types"}
issueLinkType in ("is blocked by", blocks, "is cloned by", "is duplicated by", "is caused by", "relates to"
{code}

Then in the final JQL:
{code}
project in (SCRUM) AND issuetype = story AND issueLinkType != blocks AND filter = "All issue link types" AND status not in (Done)
{code}

We recommend creating a test and dev instances of Jira prod data. This helps our Enterprise customers test upgrades and features, workarounds and fixes, I'd say "have you vetted this in a lower environment?" is one of the most common phrases I use.  The problem arises is we only take safety precautions in regard to the mail, we can set a flag in the JVM
{code:java}
-Datlassian.mail.senddisabled
-Datlassian.mail.fetchdisabled
-Datlassian.mail.popdisabled {code}
or we can disable it upon XML restore. But this still leaves the mail server and handler data in the DB and any admin can easily re-enable these mail servers. 

*There are other concerns when refreshing data:*
 * DVCS syncs
 * applinks 
 * cache replication issues if prod and dev can communicate over 40001 and 40011
 * index replication if you're doing a DB dump Jira has several bugs where it will continue to try to communicate to "offline or inactive" nodes even though they cannot reach the DB see    !https://jira.atlassian.com/secure/viewavatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=51505&avatarType=issuetype! JRASERVER-42916 - Stale node ids should automatically be removed in Jira Data Center IN PROGRESS  for more information, this can even lead to dev indexing showing up in the admin/index section in other environments 

h2. Suggested Action: 

Perhaps we could create a "lower environment" exporter or importer that strips the following from the export or import or a startup/setup task that can be run manually.
 * DVCS data
 * applinks 
 * cluster node tables 
 * mail server info and mail handlers

h2. Workaround for Manual DB refreshes: 

If you're _not_ using JIRA's XML you can do the following, if you're using an XML restore, you can perform the following after importing the data and stopping Jira.
 # Refresh the data from prod to lower environment
 # run the following _before_ starting Jira

h2. Index related tables for Data Center:

Truncate the following tables:
{code:xml}
clusternode
clusternodeheartbeat
replicatedindexoperation
{code}
h2. Mail server info

1. Delete all incoming and outgoing mail servers by truncating the following table:
{code:java}
mailserver{code}
2. Remove mail handlers
{code:java}
delete from serviceconfig where clazz='com.atlassian.jira.service.services.mail.MailFetcherService'{code}
h2. [Remove Applinks|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirakb/remove-an-application-link-from-jira-server-using-sql-285839519.html]: 

1. Find the applink ids:
{code:java}
SELECT SUBSTR(a.property_key,16,36) as "Application Key", b.propertyvalue as "Application Name" FROM propertyentry a join propertystring b on a.id=b.id where a.property_key like 'applinks.admin%name';{code}
2. After identifying the application key of the application that requires removing using the above SQL in the diagnosis section, run the following queries exactly in this order, you'll also need to run these for _each_ result from query 1.
{code:java}
DELETE FROM oauthspconsumer WHERE consumer_key IN (SELECT propertyvalue FROM propertystring WHERE id IN (SELECT id FROM propertyentry WHERE property_key LIKE 'applinks.%resultsfromfirstquery%'));
-- NOTE: For Microsoft SQLServer use the following query:
DELETE FROM oauthspconsumer WHERE consumer_key IN (SELECT CONVERT(NVARCHAR(MAX), propertyvalue) FROM propertystring WHERE id IN (SELECT id FROM propertyentry WHERE property_key LIKE 'applinks.%resultsfromfirstquery%'));{code}
{code:java}
DELETE FROM oauthconsumertoken WHERE token_key LIKE '%resultsfromfirstquery%';{code}
{code:java}
DELETE FROM oauthconsumertoken WHERE token_key LIKE '%resultsfromfirstquery%';
DELETE FROM trustedapp WHERE application_id IN (SELECT propertyvalue FROM propertystring WHERE id IN (SELECT id FROM propertyentry WHERE property_key LIKE 'applinks.%resultsfromfirstquery%')); 
-- NOTE: For Microsoft SQLServer use the following query:
DELETE FROM trustedapp WHERE application_id IN (SELECT CONVERT(NVARCHAR(MAX), propertyvalue) FROM propertystring WHERE id IN (SELECT id FROM propertyentry WHERE property_key LIKE 'applinks.%resultsfromfirstquery%'));{code}
{code:java}
DELETE FROM propertystring WHERE id IN (SELECT id FROM propertyentry WHERE property_key LIKE 'applinks.%resultsfromfirstquery%');{code}
{code:java}
DELETE FROM propertyentry WHERE property_key LIKE 'applinks.admin.resultsfromfirstquery1%';{code}
{code:java}
UPDATE propertystring SET propertyvalue = REPLACE(propertyvalue,'\n2c66970e-35f8-365f-bc65-f535d7edf1a1','') where id in (select id from propertyentry where property_key like 'applinks.global%'); {code}
h2. Remove DVCS ACCOUNTS: 
 # Delete the orgs from "AO_E8B6CC_ORGANIZATION_MAPPING":
{code:java}
delete from "AO_E8B6CC_ORGANIZATION_MAPPING"; {code}
 # Delete the repos from "AO_E8B6CC_REPOSITORY_MAPPING":
{code:java}
delete from "AO_E8B6CC_REPOSITORY_MAPPING""{code}
This will remove all connection information from JIRA to GHE.

AFTER these steps have been done you can start Jira for the first time. 

This should remove all mail servers, dvcs account info and applinks from the instance, we also have a comprehensive guide for this [here|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver/creating-a-test-environment-for-jira-966063324.html].

h3. Issue Summary
Using Safari app on iPhone when accessing a JAC ticket, and performing a pinch-to-zoom to zoom in the issue view, causes the issue to have less visible area.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Access a JAC ticket in Safari;
 # Zoom in and out on the issue view;

h3. Expected Results
The issue will render to show the portion you've zoomed in;

h3. Actual Results
The issue shows less visible area as it should;

Video:
*  [^RPReplay_Final1584479699.MP4] 

h3. Workaround
 Currently, there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available
